{meta: artist Gene Watson}
{meta: writer David Chamberlain and Jim Vest}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[C]From cotton to satin from Birmingham to [F]Manhattan
[C]From a pickup to a long [G7]limousine
[C]From cotton to satin from Birmingham to [F]Manhattan
[C]She had to [G7]follow her [C]dream
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
I saved up enough to buy [F]her one small [C]diamond
That's the year that old tractor broke [G7]down
[C]And the dream house I promised her still [F]lies by a shade [C]tree
Some old bricks and [G7]boards all [C]around
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
She begged me to take her to [F]see New York [C]City
So I mortgaged the farm and we were [G7]gone
[C]But while we were there she took [F]up with a rich [C]man
I came back to the [G7]country [C]alone
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
Now there is the garden where she [F]touched every [C]flower
There's the meadow where we walked hand in [G7]hand
[C]If only she'd waited she'd have [F]more than she dreamed [C]of
For today they [G7]struck oil on my [C]land
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
She went from cotton to satin from Birmingham to [F]Manhattan
[C]From a pickup to a lonely [G7]limousine
[C]From cotton to satin from Birmingham to [F]Manhattan
[C]She had to [G7]follow her [C]dream
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 6}
She went from cotton to satin
{end_of_verse}
